AGI - German Chancellor Olaf Scholz met Chinese President Xi Jinping in Beijing. The Chinese media reported this in the last three days of the visit of the German Chancellor in Germany's main trading partner country. "This morning President Xi Jinping met German Chancellor Scholz at the Diaoyutai State Guesthouse in Beijing," said the state broadcaster CCTV.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
With Xi, Scholz discussed a "right mouth" in Ukraine. "My meeting with President Xi will also focus on how we can contribute more to a just peace in Ukraine," the German Chancellor anticipated on X. Scholz's visit aims to strengthen economic relations, although the German leader also announced that he would try to convince Xi to use his influence to contain his Russian counterpart, Vladimir Putin, and help end the Russian war in Ukraine.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
China, which is proposed as a neutral actor in the war, was criticized by Western powers for its refusal to condemn the Russian invasion of Ukraine. Accompanied by a large delegation of ministers and businessmen, Scholz began his visit on Sunday in the south-western city of Chongqing, continued towards the economic center of Shanghai and ended in Beijing. Today he will meet Chinese premier Li Qiang and the syno-German economic committee.&nbsp;
<h2 The conflict between Kiev and Moscow
Ukraine was one of the main themes on the summit table between German Chancellor Olaf Scholz and Chinese President Xi Jinping. "The Russian aggression war in Ukraine and the rearmament of Russia have a very significant negative impact on security in Europe," said Scholz in Xi, according to a registration provided by the Chancellor's services. "They directly affect our fundamental interests - Scholz continued - and indirectly damage the entire international order because they violate a principle of the United Nations Charter, the principle of the inviolability of state borders."
&nbsp;
Scholz has been visiting China since Sunday, in his second visit since, at the end of 2021, he became Chancellor; before arriving in Beijing he was in Chongqing (southwest) and Shanghai economic capital. On the Ukrainian crisis, China calls for dialogue, opposes any use of nuclear weapons and urges respect for territorial integrity "of all countries" - which implies including Ukraine. But Beijing has never publicly condemned Moscow for the invasion of Ukraine and regularly invites to consider the security concerns of all parties, including Russia's security concerns against NATO. China and Russia have been approaching for more than a decade because of the common complaint of what they consider the "West Aegean" on the international scene. The two countries strengthened their economic, military and diplomatic cooperation after the invasion of Ukraine. Also last week Russian Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov was in Beijing.
